    "content": "**Geopolitiks Snacks** - May 2, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🕵️ Senators asked nine AI labs how many China-linked insiders can touch the crown jewels\n\nWashington has discovered that model security includes humans with badges, laptops and privileged access. Welcome to the obvious, but classified-looking, phase.\n\n- **The letters:** on May 1, Chuck Grassley and Jim Banks pressed OpenAI, Anthropic, Google, xAI, Meta, Microsoft, Amazon, Safe Superintelligence and Thinking Machines Lab on PRC espionage safeguards.\n- **The checklist:** they asked about insider-threat detection, personnel vetting, access to model weights or weight-adjacent assets, and when companies would notify the U.S. government about a security threat.\n- **The deadline:** Axios reported that the companies were asked to respond to nine questions by May 20.\n\n*The AI export-control debate has moved from chips crossing borders to employees crossing permission boundaries.*\n\n**Sources:** [Senate Judiciary Committee](https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/press/rep/releases/grassley-banks-press-american-ai-companies-on-chinese-espionage-safeguards) | [Axios](https://www.axios.com/2026/04/29/ai-firms-china-congress)\n\n---\n\n## 🧳 House Foreign Affairs is taking the AI export-control roadshow to Silicon Valley\n\nNothing says strategic competition like lawmakers checking whether the people selling the stack understand the rules meant to contain it.\n\n- **The trip:** Axios reported on May 1 that House Foreign Affairs Committee members will meet Silicon Valley companies next week to discuss AI and export controls.\n- **The guest list:** Google, Anthropic, Meta, Tesla, Intel, Applied Materials and Nvidia are among the companies expected in the conversations.\n- **The policy hook:** the committee advanced the MATCH Act earlier in April, targeting China's access to tools for manufacturing advanced chips.\n\n*Congress is no longer just writing controls from Washington. It is going to the vendors to find the gaps in the machinery.*\n\n**Sources:** [Axios](https://www.axios.com/2026/05/01/house-foreign-affairs-silicon-valley-ai-exports) | [Reuters via Investing.com](https://www.investing.com/news/stock-market-news/us-targets-chinese-chipmaking-with-proposed-export-restrictions-on-asml-and-others-4597014)\n\n---\n\n## 🧬 Cursor and Airbnb got pulled into the PRC-model dependency file\n\nCheap models were fun right up until a House committee started reading the supplier list out loud.\n\n- **The probe:** House Homeland Security and the Select Committee on China announced on April 29 a joint investigation into U.S. adoption of PRC-developed AI models.\n- **The targets:** the first letters went to Anysphere over Cursor's Composer 2 reportedly being built on Moonshot AI's Kimi, and to Airbnb over customer-service use of Alibaba's Qwen.\n- **The claim:** the committees said PRC-developed models grew from about 1% of global AI workloads in late 2024 to a reported 30% by the end of 2025.\n\n*The supply-chain question is now: not just whose cloud, but whose distilled brain is inside the workflow.*\n\n**Sources:** [House Homeland Security Committee](https://homeland.house.gov/2026/04/29/chairmen-garbarino-moolenaar-announce-joint-investigation-into-national-security-risks-posed-by-prc-ai-models/) | [Nextgov/FCW](https://www.nextgov.com/artificial-intelligence/2026/04/house-panels-probe-airbnb-anysphere-over-use-chinese-ai-models/413207/)\n\n---\n\n## 🚗 Washington wants Chinese connected cars treated like rolling surveillance hardware\n\nThe car is now a computer, the computer has radios, and Congress has noticed. Late, but with bill text.\n\n- **The bill:** Senators Bernie Moreno and Elissa Slotkin introduced the Connected Vehicle Security Act of 2026 to ban imports, sales and operation of vehicles made in China or other countries of concern.\n- **The software angle:** the proposal also bars Chinese-developed connected-vehicle technologies, including software and data systems, from American roads.\n- **The coalition:** General Motors and the CAR Coalition backed the legislation, framing it as supply-chain and industrial-security policy.\n\n*Geopolitics has reached the infotainment stack. Enjoy the firmware nationalism.*\n\n**Sources:** [Senator Bernie Moreno](https://www.moreno.senate.gov/press-releases/moreno-slotkin-bill-to-ban-chinese-vehicles-connected-components-from-u-s-market/) | [Autos Innovate](https://www.autosinnovate.org/posts/press-release/statement-on-moreno-slotkin-chinese-vehicle-ban)\n"
  }
